[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(7) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And I said . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The call to Israel to return had been slighted, and Judah, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "traitress ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or faithless, “one with falsehood,” had not taken warning from the sin or its punishment.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Turn thou unto me.—The verb may be either the second or third person, I said, thou shalt return; or, I said, she will return, as expressing a hope rather than a direct return. The latter seems, on the whole, the preferable rendering.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Turn thou unto me.—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The verb may be either the second or third person, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "I said, thou shalt return; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "or, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "I said, she will return, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "as expressing a hope rather than a direct return. The latter seems, on the whole, the preferable rendering.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jeremiah 3:7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 3:7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "After she had done all these things — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For which she might justly have been abandoned; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I said, Turn thou unto me ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Namely, and I will receive thee. Though they had forsaken both the house of David and the house of Aaron, who both had their authority from God without dispute, yet God sent his prophets among them to call them to return to him, that is, to the worship of him only, not insisting so much upon their return to the house of David as to that of Aaron. We do not read that Elijah, that great prophet, ever mentioned their returning to the former, but only to the faithful service of the true God. It is serious and genuine piety that God regards more than any ritual observances, whether with respect to matters civil or religious. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But she returned not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Which God observed, and with which he was much displeased; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and her treacherous sister Judah saw it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— A ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sister, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "because descended from the same common stock, Abraham and Jacob; and as Israel had the character of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "back-slider, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "so Judah is called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "treacherous, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "because, though she professed to keep close to God when Israel had backslidden, and adhered to the kings and priests that were of God’s own appointing, yet she proved treacherous, false, and unfaithful to her profession and promises, as is stated in the following verses.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3:6-11 If we mark the crimes of those who break off from a religious profession, and the consequences, we see abundant reason to shun evil ways. It is dreadful to be proved more criminal than those who have actually perished in their sins; yet it will be small comfort in everlasting punishment, for them to know that others were viler than they.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or, \"And I said (i. e., within myself), After she has done all these things, she will return to me.\" But she did not return.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Treacherous - literally, \"Falsehood,\" i. e., false, faithless. The character of the two sisters is plainly marked. Samaria is apostate; she abandons Yahweh's worship altogether. Judah maintains the form only; her secret desires are set upon the orgies of pagan worship. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Treacherous - literally, \"Falsehood,\" i. e., false, faithless. The character of the two sisters is plainly marked. Samaria is apostate; she abandons Yahweh's worship altogether. Judah maintains the form only; her secret desires are set upon the orgies of pagan worship. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
